19:02.708 --> 19:08.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look, the only thing I would ask
of the Clinton
campaign and many of their
sympathizers is,

19:08.481 --> 19:12.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when you are asked a question
about Hillary
Clinton, try not to say Donald
Trump every

19:12.051 --> 19:13.019 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
other word.

19:13.052 --> 19:14.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is where criticisms like
that come from.

19:14.920 --> 19:17.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think people -- if you have a
real debate
on the issues, you go back and
look at the

19:17.923 --> 19:21.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
radical Islamic speech from
Monday, you go
back and look at the law and
order speech

19:21.394 --> 19:26.298 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the minority community
speech yesterday,
you find that that
characterization is patently

19:26.332 --> 19:28.067 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
false.

19:28.100 --> 19:30.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I think I
was hearing
Robert Costa quote people he was
talking to

19:30.269 --> 19:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from inside the campaign, but we
can straighten
that out later.

19:33.973 --> 19:38.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kellyanne Conway, again, the
newly named campaign
manager for Donald Trump, thank
you very much.

19:38.677 --> 19:45.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KELLYANNE CONWAY: Thank you,
Judy.

19:45.918 --> 19:55.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Two major
disasters in two
different parts of the country
have sent tens

19:55.895 --> 20:01.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of thousands of people fleeing
from their
homes, and caused millions of
dollars in damage.

20:01.133 --> 20:06.105 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are these just freak events, or
are they in
some way related to climate
change?

20:06.138 --> 20:07.807 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
William Brangham brings us the
latest.

20:07.840 --> 20:12.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: It's called
the Blue Cut
Fire, and it's wreaking havoc in
Southern

20:12.778 --> 20:14.647 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
California.

20:14.680 --> 20:18.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The massive blaze closed major
roadways like
part of Interstate-15 that
connects Los Angeles

20:18.317 --> 20:19.919 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Las Vegas.

20:19.952 --> 20:24.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And last night, officials issued
evacuation
orders for more than 34,000
homes.

20:24.256 --> 20:26.092 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's some 82,000 people.

20:26.125 --> 20:31.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: I think this is the worst
that I have
ever seen, you know?

20:31.330 --> 20:37.036 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's kind of getting used to
the idea
of being homeless.

20:37.069 --> 20:41.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The fire
erupted yesterday
in the Cajon Pass, a critical
corridor just

20:41.707 --> 20:45.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
north of San Bernardino, only 60
miles from
Los Angeles.

20:45.945 --> 20:49.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It quickly expanded to more than
45 square
miles.

20:49.215 --> 20:55.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ten air tankers, 15 helicopters
and some 1,300
firefighters were deployed
within 24 hours.

20:55.888 --> 20:57.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They faced hot and windy
conditions.

20:57.857 --> 20:59.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL WAKOSKI, San Bernardino
County Fire
Battalion Chief: The fuels are
extremely dry

20:59.859 --> 21:03.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and very explosive this time of
year.

21:03.095 --> 21:08.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in my 40 years of fighting
fire, I have
never seen fire behavior so
extreme as it

21:08.567 --> 21:10.369 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
was yesterday.

21:10.402 --> 21:11.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK HARTWIG, San Bernardino
County Fire Chief:
I was able to get up this
morning and get

21:11.937 --> 21:14.240 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
some eyes on it from the air.

21:14.273 --> 21:19.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In a word, it was devastating, a
lot of homes
lost yesterday.

21:19.979 --> 21:23.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There'll be a lot of families
that come home
to nothing.

21:23.315 --> 21:27.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Governor Jerry
Brown declared
a state of emergency for the
Blue Cut area,

21:27.319 --> 21:31.657 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as he did earlier this week for
a major blaze
north of San Francisco.

21:31.690 --> 21:33.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That fire has since started to
fade.

21:33.792 --> 21:38.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The man suspected of sparking
it, as well
as 16 smaller fires over the
last year, has

21:38.397 --> 21:41.934 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
now been charged with arson.

21:41.967 --> 21:46.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Seventeen hundred miles across
the country,
a different kind of disaster is
unfolding

21:46.205 --> 21:51.210 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Louisiana, where some of the
worst floods
in history have hit the state.

21:51.243 --> 21:55.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As the water begins to recede in
some parts,
the numbers are stark.

21:55.347 --> 22:01.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At least 11 people have died,
30,000 people
have been rescued, and 40,000
homes damaged.

22:01.720 --> 22:06.358 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: We lost everything, God,
just about.

22:06.392 --> 22:12.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We got out safely and all of our
friends are
safe, so that's the main thing.

22:12.831 --> 22:17.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So far, about
68,000 people
have signed up for assistance
from the Federal

22:17.403 --> 22:19.271 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Emergency Management Agency.

22:19.305 --> 22:23.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The American Red Cross says this
flooding
has triggered its largest
disaster operation

22:23.976 --> 22:26.946 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
since Superstorm Sandy in 2012.

22:26.979 --> 22:31.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The catastrophes in California
and Louisiana
have again raised the question:
Are these

22:31.684 --> 22:35.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
events caused in part by global
climate change?

22:35.054 --> 22:40.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Both events follow a July that
was the planet's
single hottest month since
records began in

22:40.092 --> 22:45.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the 19th century, and many
computer models
have indicated that, as
temperatures rise,

22:45.064 --> 22:48.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
droughts and extreme weather are
likely to
follow.

22:48.300 --> 22:52.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To help us sort out what's
driving these extreme
events, we turn to two
scientists well-versed

22:52.871 --> 22:54.640 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in these matters.

22:54.673 --> 22:58.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Barry Keim is a climatologist
for the state
of Louisiana and a professor at
Louisiana

22:58.277 --> 23:04.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
State University, and Adam Sobel
is a professor
of environmental science at
Columbia University.

23:04.116 --> 23:07.720 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He also directs its Initiative
on Extreme
Weather and Climate.

23:07.753 --> 23:08.954 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you both for being here.

23:08.988 --> 23:11.523 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Barry, I would like to start
with you.

23:11.557 --> 23:14.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before we get into the science
of all of this,
can you just tell us, how are
things in Baton

23:14.460 --> 23:16.328 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Rouge right now?

23:16.362 --> 23:18.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARRY KEIM, Louisiana State
University: Well,
in Baton Rouge, they are
improving, but across

23:18.130 --> 23:20.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the broader area, there still
are some issues.

23:20.866 --> 23:24.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Things are slowly starting to
settle down
or simmer down a little bit.

23:24.036 --> 23:28.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, right now, across most of
my immediate
region, people have already
started ripping

23:28.540 --> 23:30.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out carpets and gutting houses.

23:30.142 --> 23:32.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, we're already starting the
cleanup.

23:32.144 --> 23:36.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, this was
obviously a
historic amount of rainfall that
fell on your

23:36.482 --> 23:38.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
state and that flooded you all
out.

23:38.851 --> 23:44.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can you give us a sense of the
context of
how serious these storms were,
and should

23:44.290 --> 23:46.792 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we be thinking about these in
terms of climate
change?

23:46.825 --> 23:48.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BARRY KEIM: This event was -- it
was a tropical
disturbance.

23:48.894 --> 23:54.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a very weak -- in fact,
it -- I would
classify it practically as an
easterly wave.

23:54.700 --> 23:56.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the amount of rainfall
amounts, as I suggested,
were staggering.

23:56.902 --> 24:04.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just to put this in perspective,
a 100-year
rain event in this region is
roughly 14 inches.

24:04.176 --> 24:07.379 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A 1,000-year event is about 21
inches.

24:07.413 --> 24:11.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, we have about eight sites,
seven or
eight sites across Southeast
Louisiana or

24:11.317 --> 24:14.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
South Central Louisiana that
exceeded the
1,000-year mark.

24:14.520 --> 24:19.992 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, we have one site
that had 30
-- over 31 inches of rain.

24:20.025 --> 24:24.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, 1,000-year event is 21
inches, and this
was 31 inches.

24:24.129 --> 24:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that ought to give you some
context on
just how severe this rainstorm
was across

24:27.566 --> 24:29.268 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this area.

24:29.301 --> 24:32.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In that
context, do you
think of this as something that
is -- what

24:32.438 --> 24:36.075 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we would expect to see with
climate change,
or is that not part of your
thinking?

24:36.108 --> 24:41.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARRY KEIM: Well, no single
event really tells
you anything about climate
change specifically,

24:42.014 --> 24:43.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and even one year's worth of
events.

24:43.782 --> 24:46.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, admittedly, this past year
has been very
strange.

24:46.185 --> 24:48.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We had the floods in South
Carolina.

24:48.520 --> 24:49.788 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Texas had some serious floods.

24:49.822 --> 24:52.791 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We even had a major flood
earlier this year
in Louisiana.

24:52.825 --> 24:57.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, we even had an early
one back in
this past October which was
quite extraordinary.

24:57.896 --> 25:01.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it does seem like there is
something unusual
going on.

25:01.300 --> 25:07.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I still wouldn't quite
characterize this
as being a sign that the climate
has officially

25:07.039 --> 25:08.107 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
changed.

25:08.140 --> 25:09.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are just in a very unusual
period right
now.

25:09.975 --> 25:13.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this could be indicative of
climate change,
but it's way, way too early.

25:13.479 --> 25:17.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we need a lot more data and
understanding
of the science to be able to say
something

25:17.516 --> 25:18.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
conclusively like that.

25:18.951 --> 25:22.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Adam Sobel, I
would put
the same question to you.

25:22.287 --> 25:24.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In California, we have seen this
historic
drought.

25:24.723 --> 25:26.258 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It has dried out the landscape.

25:26.291 --> 25:30.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is partly why we have seen
these explosive
fires across the state there.

25:30.396 --> 25:35.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, again droughts are not
unusual for California,
the same way floods are not
unusual for Louisiana.

25:35.501 --> 25:37.369 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How do you see these in relation
to climate
change?

25:37.403 --> 25:41.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM SOBEL, Columbia University:
Well, I think
you have to talk about each
event separately.

25:41.173 --> 25:42.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So let's start with the
Louisiana event.

25:42.875 --> 25:46.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the California situation
is a little
bit different and has been going
on for a

25:46.278 --> 25:47.746 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
number of years.

25:47.780 --> 25:49.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there have actually been a
few studies
specifically on that event.

25:49.648 --> 25:54.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But since we're talking about
Louisiana and
the floods now, just for some
general context,

25:54.920 --> 25:58.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, across the United
States, as well
as most places in the world
where there is

25:58.791 --> 26:03.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
adequate data to ask the
question, we have
seen increases over the last
decades, or in

26:03.662 --> 26:08.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some cases the last century, in
the extremity
of severe rain events.

26:08.300 --> 26:11.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we see heavy rain events
becoming heavier
and a larger fraction of the
rain falling

26:12.004 --> 26:13.806 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
at heavy events.

26:13.839 --> 26:17.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is what our climate
projections tell
us should happen as the climate
warms, although

26:17.509 --> 26:21.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to uncertain degrees, but it's
qualitatively
consistent.

26:21.146 --> 26:26.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we expect it on physical
grounds, as a
warming climate means that there
is more water

26:26.118 --> 26:27.820 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
vapor in the atmosphere.

26:27.853 --> 26:32.224 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, it's true that each
individual event
is a result of many factors, and
climate change

26:32.257 --> 26:35.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is at most one of them, and
usually a small
one.

26:35.227 --> 26:38.363 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So a lot of things have to
happen for an extreme
event to occur.

26:38.397 --> 26:39.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Otherwise, it wouldn't be an
extreme event.

26:40.032 --> 26:43.335 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so climate change can at
most push the
odds a little bit in one
direction.

26:43.368 --> 26:49.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I mean, we now have a new
emerging area
of science called extreme event
attribution,

26:49.475 --> 26:53.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where people actually do studies
and have
ways of making probabilistic
statements.

26:53.278 --> 26:57.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't ever say this event
was caused by
climate change or this single
event is conclusive

26:57.249 --> 26:59.051 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
evidence of climate change.

26:59.084 --> 27:02.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you can say that climate
change appears
to have made it such a percent
more probable,

27:02.588 --> 27:06.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or given that it occurred, make
it such and
such percent more extreme.

27:06.291 --> 27:09.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those studies haven't yet been
done on the
Louisiana event.

27:09.595 --> 27:11.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My guess is that they will be
done pretty
soon.

27:11.463 --> 27:13.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They can get done pretty quickly
now.

27:13.332 --> 27:17.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would cautiously predict
that they are
going to show some increase in
the likelihood

27:17.536 --> 27:20.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of this happening due to climate
change, although
I wouldn't want to put a number
on it.

27:21.006 --> 27:22.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, that is the sort of broad
context.

27:22.975 --> 27:26.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it is the kind of thing
we expect
to see more as the future
proceeds.

27:26.345 --> 27:28.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's the kind of thing we
have been seeing.

27:28.580 --> 27:34.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I agree that to make
stronger statements
than that about a specific
event, it is certainly

27:34.586 --> 27:36.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
possible to overstate the
connection.

27:36.488 --> 27:39.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there is a lot of science
behind the statement
that there may be some
connection there.

27:39.691 --> 27:41.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Barry, back to
you.

27:41.760 --> 27:45.264 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm just curious, do you think
that this is
what we have just got to become
accustomed

27:45.297 --> 27:49.902 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to, that what was once
considered an extreme
event is now just the new
normal?

27:49.935 --> 27:52.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, if so, what does that mean
for policy-makers?

27:52.037 --> 27:56.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BARRY KEIM: Yes, well, we're
certainly in
a period right now where we have
seen quite

27:56.909 --> 27:58.677 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a bit -- quite a few extremes.

27:58.710 --> 28:02.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And -- but we have had some
periods in the
past where we have had
clustering of really

28:03.015 --> 28:08.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
big, catastrophic rainfall
events in the past
as well.

28:08.086 --> 28:13.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I tell you, the last decade
or so really
does raise some eyebrows, and
very, very suspicious.

28:13.592 --> 28:20.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And as what this means for
policy implications,
I mean, this is just so complex,
so politically

28:20.832 --> 28:27.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
loaded, that, I mean, it's
really tough to
navigate through these waters,
so to speak.

28:27.406 --> 28:33.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, yes, it is really hard
to say a whole
lot conclusively on what kind of
policy should

28:33.211 --> 28:35.514 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
proceed as a result of these
recent extremes.

28:35.547 --> 28:40.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Adam, with
relation to the
fire in California and the many
people appointed

28:40.686 --> 28:46.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the very long drought that
has dried out
much of California and makes
these fires more

28:46.725 --> 28:51.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
common and more violent when
they actually
occur, how do you see climate
change in relation

28:51.163 --> 28:52.598 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to that particular event?

28:52.631 --> 28:54.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ADAM SOBEL: Right.

28:54.399 --> 28:56.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if we look at the drought in
California,
there have actually been several
studies of

28:56.802 --> 28:59.104 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it, some of it done by my
colleagues here
at Columbia.

28:59.137 --> 29:03.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those studies actually show
the complexity
of studying events like this,
because the

29:03.075 --> 29:05.510 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
answer actually depends how you
ask the question.

29:05.544 --> 29:09.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you ask about just the lack
of rainfall
-- of course, the cause of a
drought is just

29:09.548 --> 29:13.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
