studies have
tended to come to a conclusion
that it's not

29:13.318 --> 29:16.188 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
-- this event is not
fundamentally caused
by climate change.

29:16.221 --> 29:20.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That said, once you have a lack
of rainfall,
the hotter temperatures that we
see as a result

29:20.492 --> 29:25.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of human influence on climate
cause water
to evaporate from the soils more
quickly,

29:25.063 --> 29:29.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and so you have overall a dryer
land surface
and lower reservoirs and all of
that.

29:29.434 --> 29:31.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that, there, there is a
climate change
influence.

29:31.169 --> 29:35.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if you ask about the lack of
rainfall,
this event appears to be largely
natural,

29:35.107 --> 29:36.942 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is what the studies have shown.

29:36.975 --> 29:43.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you ask about the overall
dryness of
California, there does seem to
be some influence

29:43.281 --> 29:45.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of higher temperature, which is
a result of
climate change.

29:45.550 --> 29:49.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the studies have come to
different conclusions,
in part because they ask
different questions.

29:49.788 --> 29:54.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I think that is the
complicated answer
to that question, as far as we
know now.

29:54.292 --> 29:58.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right,
Adam Sobel, Barry
Keim, thank you both very much
