out it was going to be.

33:49.461 --> 33:53.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we have survived before
without being
in the European Union.

33:53.899 --> 33:56.101 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we will survive again.

33:56.134 --> 33:58.003 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm sure we will.

33:58.036 --> 34:02.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER GLASSE: Despite the
anti-Europe sentiment
here, this harbor town has deep
historical

34:03.008 --> 34:05.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ties with the continent.

34:05.543 --> 34:10.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dutch Prince William of Orange
landed here
on the 5th of November, 1688,
and he became

34:10.582 --> 34:13.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the king of England, ruling
alongside Queen
Mary.

34:14.019 --> 34:19.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Napoleon Bonaparte never
actually set foot
on land, but his ship was just
offshore before

34:19.291 --> 34:21.059 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he was sent into exile.

34:21.092 --> 34:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over tea, local historian Edgar
Lawrence says
it's no surprise Britons voted
to leave.

34:26.631 --> 34:33.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDGAR LAWRENCE, Historian: I'm
old enough
to have voted for the common
market, but what

34:33.038 --> 34:38.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
