the software
that is the backbone of the
Internet today.

38:51.529 --> 38:55.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He is now chairman and CEO of
Farsight Security,
a computer security firm.

38:55.700 --> 38:57.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ellen Nakashima, what happened
this weekend?

38:57.902 --> 38:59.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What got released?

38:59.771 --> 39:01.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELLEN NAKASHIMA, The Washington
Post: Over
the weekend, apparently on
Saturday, mysteriously,

39:02.006 --> 39:12.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a cache of NSA hacking tools was
released
online through file-sharing
sites such as

39:12.050 --> 39:14.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BitTorrent and Dropbox.

39:14.586 --> 39:21.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really wasn't noticed until
about Monday,
when the computer security
community started

39:21.059 --> 39:25.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commenting on it and questions
arose as to
whether or not the NSA had been
hacked.

39:25.997 --> 39:30.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Paul
Vixie, if these
lock picks, these digital tools
to try break

39:30.401 --> 39:34.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into different systems out are
out in the
open now, these are the tools
that the American

39:34.272 --> 39:38.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
government was using, what is
the consequence,
if it is in the public sphere?

39:38.476 --> 39:44.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL VIXIE, Chairman and CEO,
Farsight Security:
Well, I think, every day,
everybody is trying

39:44.916 --> 39:46.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to hack everybody.

39:46.150 --> 39:49.487 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, this is not huge news.

39:49.520 --> 39:55.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What's big news about it is that
these tools
were built by the U.S.
government.

39:55.693 --> 40:00.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some of the lock picks, as you
call them,
are now obsolete.

40:00.632 --> 40:06.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They are relying on
vulnerabilities that have
since been closed, because the
files are about

40:06.271 --> 40:08.072 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
3 years old.

40:08.106 --> 40:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But at least one of them is
active against
a very current piece of
equipment from Cisco.

40:12.477 --> 40:20.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is going to lead to a lot
of break-ins
while the patches are prepared
and shipped

40:20.151 --> 40:21.919 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and then applied.

40:21.953 --> 40:24.856 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Ellen
Nakashima, what about
the idea that some of these are
as recent

40:24.889 --> 40:28.660 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
