40:28.693 --> 40:33.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does the NSA know, if this was a
hack, if
this was something more recent?

40:33.097 --> 40:37.168 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ELLEN NAKASHIMA: The NSA
officially is not
commenting.

40:37.201 --> 40:45.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But former NSA operators,
personnel I have
interviewed were -- actually
recognized the

40:45.810 --> 40:51.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tooled that were released and
said they were,
indeed, legitimate.

40:51.282 --> 40:54.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they don't believe that the
NSA was actually
hacked.

40:54.886 --> 41:04.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They think it is more likely
that perhaps
one of the operators at the
agency inadvertently

41:04.062 --> 41:15.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
uploaded a tool set, an entire
tool set of
tools to a server, a staging
server in cyberspace,

41:15.306 --> 41:20.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and didn't recognize that, and
didn't pull
it back down.

41:20.144 --> 41:27.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once it was out there, other
adversaries,
other spy agencies around the
world are also

41:27.518 --> 41:30.254 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
sometimes sitting on these same
servers.

41:30.288 --> 41:37.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of them might have noticed
it, got it,
took a copy of it, and got it,
without the

41:37.061 --> 41:38.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NSA realizing it.

41:38.930 --> 41:44.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Paul Vixie,
how many people,
companies, governments does this
make vulnerable?

41:44.435 --> 41:52.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL VIXIE: I haven't seen an
estimate of
the market size, but, really, we
have got

41:52.944 --> 41:57.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
at least one of these
vulnerabilities that
is still current, and the patch
is being prepared

41:57.582 --> 41:59.350 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

41:59.384 --> 42:03.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unfortunately, some of the ones
that are not
current are also going to work,
because many

42:04.021 --> 42:06.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enterprise networks are not
patched up to
date.

42:06.924 --> 42:12.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They can't afford the constant
churn of updating
their equipment, updating their
software.

42:12.463 --> 42:18.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so even though some of the
vulnerabilities
that have been used by these
tools are no

42:18.770 --> 42:24.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
longer current, they're still
going to -- those
picks are still going to fit
quite a few locks.

42:24.776 --> 42:31.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't really -- I would say,
in order of
magnitude, anywhere between
one-tenth and

42:31.215 --> 42:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one-half of the customer bases
for the largest
firewall vendors should really
be worried

42:37.488 --> 42:38.823 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
right now.

42:38.856 --> 42:40.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That still
sounds like a
pretty large number.

42:40.658 --> 42:43.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL VIXIE: Yes, that is a large
number.

42:43.895 --> 42:46.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Internet was originally
academic.

42:46.564 --> 42:50.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when it was built, every one
that could
reach you was trustworthy.

42:50.268 --> 42:56.240 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, that changed in
the mid-'90s,
when we commercialized and
privatized the

42:56.274 --> 42:58.042 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Internet.

42:58.075 --> 43:01.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And at that time, we started
developing this
firewall technology that was
meant to limit

43:01.245 --> 43:05.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of who could reach you or
how various
people could reach you.

43:05.716 --> 43:11.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what that means is, the
inside of these
networks is very soft, full of
soft targets,

43:11.989 --> 43:15.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and tends to rely on firewall to
keep it safe.

43:15.693 --> 43:22.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, any time you have a key that
will unlock
the firewall and let you do
whatever you want

43:22.133 --> 43:24.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the other side, you suddenly
have a very
target-rich environment.

43:24.969 --> 43:29.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Ellen, the
people that you
have spoken to, are they
concerned that kind

43:29.207 --> 43:36.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the design of these keys
would tip off
to whoever is using these tools
exactly who

43:36.047 --> 43:41.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the NSA targets, how they target
them, how
they create the breaches in
these firewalls?

43:41.652 --> 43:43.421 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ELLEN NAKASHIMA: Well,
absolutely.

43:43.454 --> 43:48.926 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that is one of the issues
with, you know,
a disclosure like this.

43:48.960 --> 43:53.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I should say there are also
some former
employees who think it's more
likely that

43:53.798 --> 44:00.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some disgruntled insider stole
all the tools
and then put them out there,
perhaps for some

44:00.338 --> 44:02.140 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
personal profit.

44:02.173 --> 44:09.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in any case, now that they
are out there,
they are available to other
hackers, other

44:09.514 --> 44:17.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spy agencies who could either
target companies
running these firewalls, or also
look and

44:17.722 --> 44:24.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
watch to see what the NSA is
targeting and
exfiltrating as well.

44:24.562 --> 44:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Ellen, in the
context the
sort of cyberwar that seems to
be escalating

44:29.467 --> 44:34.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
between Russia and other
countries, the fact
that this happens now, what are
your sources

44:34.405 --> 44:40.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
telling you about how these
tools could end
up in the wrong hands in a
political context?

44:40.945 --> 44:42.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ELLEN NAKASHIMA: Yes.

44:42.680 --> 44:48.519 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Look, it's -- I don't think we
have any hard
evidence as to who is behind the
release.

44:48.553 --> 44:56.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's, at this point, I think,
largely circumstantial
that it -- some people think it
might be Russia.

44:56.961 --> 45:03.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The timing is certainly notable,
or suspect,
coming, as you noted, on the
heels of some

45:03.968 --> 45:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the hacks of the DNC and the
DCCC and the
releases of hacked e-mails from
the DNC that

45:12.610 --> 45:20.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have been linked to Russia or,
more recently,
of hacked personal cell phone
numbers and

45:20.518 --> 45:22.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
e-mail addresses of Democratic
lawmakers.

45:22.353 --> 45:25.890 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That also appears to be coming
from Russia.

45:25.923 --> 45:34.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, some people think that maybe
