provocations.

45:42.273 --> 45:47.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a signal to them to say,
hey, you know,
if you are thinking about
retaliating in some

45:47.812 --> 45:54.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
way, calling us out, stepping up
sanctions,
or even responding in kind in
cyberspace,

45:54.085 --> 45:56.621 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think twice, because we can
cause you some
pain.

45:56.654 --> 46:01.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, finally,
briefly, Paul
Vixie, is there concern in the
computer security

46:01.359 --> 46:05.162 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
committee -- community whether
the NSA can
keep its secrets safe?

46:05.196 --> 46:08.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL VIXIE: There is.

46:08.332 --> 46:14.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The NSA needs a lot of fairly
controversial
data and tools in order to
accomplish its

46:14.705 --> 46:16.507 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mission.

46:16.540 --> 46:22.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we depend on those type --
that kind of
data, those kind of tools not
being generally

46:22.513 --> 46:24.315 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
available.

46:24.348 --> 46:29.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, with this disclosure and
with the Edward
Snowden disclosures of a couple
of years ago,

46:29.854 --> 46:35.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there is some concern that maybe
there are
some types of data, some types
of tools that

46:35.526 --> 46:40.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
