tick.

47:07.291 --> 47:09.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the latest in our weekly
Leading MD+IT /MD-IT /Edge
series.

47:09.794 --> 47:11.762 align:left position:25%,start line:80% size:75%
MD+IT /MD-IT /
MIKE GARCIA, Geologist,
University of Hawaii:

47:11.796 --> 47:13.597 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

47:13.631 --> 47:16.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: If you want to
learn what makes
a volcano erupt, you need to go
right to the

47:16.934 --> 47:22.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
otherworldly source, the
crunchy, oozing,
red-hot source.

47:22.606 --> 47:25.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At least, that's what geologist
Mike Garcia
does.

47:25.509 --> 47:27.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MIKE GARCIA: Voila.

47:27.545 --> 47:29.580 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Wow.

47:29.613 --> 47:30.915 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's amazing.

47:30.948 --> 47:32.316 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Amazing, indeed.

47:32.349 --> 47:35.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Welcome to the most studied
volcano in the
world, Kilauea.

47:36.020 --> 47:41.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Garcia and I came here to this
surreal landscape
on Hawaii's Big Island by
helicopter.

47:41.358 --> 47:47.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On our way, we got a glimpse of
the red rock
cauldron of magma through the
sulfur-tainted

47:47.064 --> 47:48.532 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
steam.

47:48.566 --> 47:52.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kilauea is one of the longest
currently erupting
volcanoes on the planet.

47:52.436 --> 47:55.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The lava started flowing in
January of 1983.

47:55.072 --> 48:00.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: So, the mantle is
producing an
enormous amount of hot material
that's coming

48:00.778 --> 48:02.446 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out of Kilauea.

48:02.480 --> 48:07.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is probably one of the most
active periods
of the historical record of
Kilauea.

48:07.218 --> 48:13.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: The eruption
waxes and wanes,
at times spewing fountains of
lava, and, in

48:13.224 --> 48:16.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the 1990s, threatening and
destroying nearby
homes.

48:16.894 --> 48:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, of late, it's been more
spectacle than
menace, a slow-motion window
into what lies

48:23.234 --> 48:25.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
beneath the surface.

48:25.269 --> 48:30.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Through it all, there is one
constant here
besides flowing lava: Garcia.

48:30.307 --> 48:35.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has been studying Kilauea for
30 years,
hoping to improve eruption
forecasting.

48:35.780 --> 48:39.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: Well, with most
volcanoes, you
want to know when it's going to
erupt.

48:39.984 --> 48:42.019 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so that's a primary concern.

48:42.052 --> 48:46.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in this case, where we have
an eruption
that's been going on for over 30
years, the

48:46.190 --> 48:48.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
big question is, when is it
going to stop?

48:48.159 --> 48:54.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: He comes here
looking for data,
in this case a piece of freshly
cooked earth

48:54.732 --> 48:56.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
just out of the oven.

48:56.600 --> 49:03.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He dunks it in water, freezing
the moment
and its chemical composition in
time, a geological

49:03.407 --> 49:04.975 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Instagram packed with data.

49:05.009 --> 49:07.044 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MIKE GARCIA: We know its
birthday.

49:07.077 --> 49:09.313 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We know when it was erupted.

49:09.346 --> 49:12.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you might ask, well, why do
we -- why
do we care?

49:12.349 --> 49:16.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because the lava composition
changes hourly,
daily, or -- and even monthly.

49:16.687 --> 49:23.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And somewhere in
there might
be some sort of telltale sign of
whether it's

49:23.494 --> 49:25.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to continue erupting or
not, right?

49:25.529 --> 49:27.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MIKE GARCIA: Absolutely.

49:27.264 --> 49:30.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In science, one of the key
things we do now
are time series studies, where
we collect

49:30.668 --> 49:35.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
samples repeatedly during the
course of an
eruption or in the ocean,
because it's evolving

49:35.573 --> 49:37.474 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
all the time.

49:37.508 --> 49:42.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Back in his lab
at the University
of Hawaii in Honolulu, graduate
student Kendra

49:42.713 --> 49:49.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lynn does her part to understand
Kilauea,
shaving rocks into 30-micron
slices, and then

49:49.353 --> 49:52.656 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
analyzing them using an electron
microprobe.

49:52.690 --> 49:56.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She is interested in this green
mineral called
olivine.

49:56.327 --> 49:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is the most common mineral
that forms at
Kilauea.

49:59.730 --> 50:01.465 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What can we learn from it?

50:01.498 --> 50:03.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENDRA LYNN, Graduate Student,
University
of Hawaii: Because it's the
first thing to

50:03.267 --> 50:06.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crystallize in these magmas, it
tells us a
lot about the mantle source,
where the magmas

50:06.804 --> 50:08.072 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
came from.

50:08.105 --> 50:10.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it can also tell us a lot
about the magma's
history.

50:10.674 --> 50:15.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: This is just one
of many tests
the team routinely conducts to
analyze the

50:15.212 --> 50:18.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
elements and isotopes in the
newborn rocks.

50:18.215 --> 50:22.987 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE GARCIA: Each of the
processes within
the volcano leaves a
fingerprint.

50:23.020 --> 50:28.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, over the years, we have been
able to develop
an understanding of what those
fingerprints

50:28.993 --> 50:32.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are and what they tell us about
what's going
on in the volcano.

50:32.263 --> 50:33.464 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, where are we
right now?

50:33.497 --> 50:35.432 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What is this?

50:35.466 --> 50:37.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: We're looking at
the rock collection
we have from the Pu'u 'O'o
eruption, as well

50:37.835 --> 50:39.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as some of the other Hawaiian
eruptions.

50:39.737 --> 50:44.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: And over the
years he has amassed
an impressive collection of
rocks, not just

50:44.942 --> 50:48.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from Kilauea, but from volcanoes
all over
the Hawaiian islands.

50:48.679 --> 50:54.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: So, this is July 23
of 1997.

50:54.551 --> 50:56.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this one looks a little
grayer.

50:56.353 --> 50:58.522 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Yes, it's not
quite as shiny,
for whatever reason.

50:58.555 --> 50:59.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why would that be?

50:59.556 --> 51:00.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: But you can see the
imprint.

51:00.824 --> 51:02.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, it was a little cooler at
the time it
was quenched.

51:02.993 --> 51:04.361 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ah, I see.

51:04.395 --> 51:06.530 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
If only these rocks could talk.

51:06.563 --> 51:10.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fortunately, Garcia is pretty
adept at reading
them.

51:10.501 --> 51:13.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of the things he focuses on
is the temperature
of the lava.

51:13.771 --> 51:17.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MIKE GARCIA: So, what we have
seen is a long-term
decrease.

51:17.408 --> 51:20.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Initially, the lava temperature
was low.

51:20.678 --> 51:21.645 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It increased.

51:21.679 --> 51:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The eruption roared upward.

51:23.547 --> 51:28.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now it's been slowly waning
as -- and
we see the temperature of the
lava is indicating

51:28.886 --> 51:30.054 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a decrease.

51:30.087 --> 51:34.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we think this eruption might
end in the
near future.

51:34.358 --> 51:36.894 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it's ended several times in
the past.

51:36.927 --> 51:41.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was quiet in 1997 for a
month, and then
it restarted.

51:41.899 --> 51:47.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Back at the lava
flow, Garcia
told me his work is not as
dangerous as it

51:47.271 --> 51:51.308 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
